## Example: Building an L-Shape

Here's a more complex example. Karel needs to build an L-shape: a row of beepers along the bottom, then a column going up. The problem is decomposed into `build_base()` and `build_column()`, plus helper functions for turning.

<KarelEnvironment config={houseExample} />

Notice how the main program is just two lines: `build_base()` then `build_column()`. All the details of *how* to build each part are tucked away inside the functions. That's the beauty of decomposition!

---

## When to Create a Function

Here are some guidelines for when to break code into a function:

- **When you repeat the same steps** — If you're writing the same sequence of commands more than once, make it a function
- **When a chunk of code has a clear purpose** — If you can describe what a group of commands does in a few words, that's a good function name
- **When your code is getting long** — If your main program is more than 10–15 lines, look for sections you can pull out into functions

Good decomposition makes your code **easier to read**, **easier to debug**, and **easier to reuse**.

